{"title_page": "Kostas Antetokounmpo", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Kostas Antetokounmpo\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| league = [[NBA]]\n| team = Los Angeles Lakers\n| number = 37\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lbs = 220\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|11|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Athens]], Greece\n| nationality = Greek\n| high_school = [[Dominican High School (Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin)|Dominican]]<br>([[Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin]])\n| college = [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]] (2017\u20132018)\n| draft_year = 2018\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 60\n| draft_team = [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n| career_start = 2018\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2018|full=y}}\n| team1 = [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n| years2 = 2018\u20132019\n| team2 = \u2192[[Texas Legends]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team3 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| years4 = 2019\u2013present\n| team4 = \u2192[[South Bay Lakers]]\n| profile = kostas_antetokounmpo\n| bbr = antetko01\n}}\n'''Kostas Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo''' ({{respell|AHN|teh|tuh|KOOM|poh|}}; {{lang-el|\u039a\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf}}) (born November 20, 1997)<ref>[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/126901/sid/12474/tid/291/_/2016_FIBA_U20_European_Championship_Division_B/index.html Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo DOB: 20 Nov.1997 Place of birth: Athens (GRE).]</ref> is a Greek professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), on a [[two-way contract]] with the [[South Bay Lakers]] of the [[NBA G League]]. He was drafted 60th overall by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] in the [[2018 NBA draft]], and his draft rights were then traded to the Dallas Mavericks.<ref name=\"realgm\">{{cite web|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo|url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Kostas-Antetokounmpo/Summary/93018|publisher=[[RealGM]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He attended and played [[college basketball|collegiate level basketball]] in the United States for the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton Flyers]]. Two of his older brothers, [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] and [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]], both play for the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lakers claim Giannis' younger brother, Kostas |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/27239420/lakers-claim-giannis-younger-brother-kostas |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 17, 2020 |date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAntetokounmpo was born in [[Sepolia]] in [[Athens, Greece]]. His parents were immigrants from [[Nigeria]]. As a youth, he began playing the sport of basketball with the junior youth teams of [[Filathlitikos BC|Filathlitikos]], in Athens.\n\n==High school career==\nAfter his older brother [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] was drafted by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] in the [[2013 NBA draft]], Antetokounmpo, along with his parents and his younger brother, Alexis, moved to Milwaukee. He attended [[Dominican High School (Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin)|Dominican High School]] in [[Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin]],<ref name=\"dominican\">{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Mark|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo making a name for himself at Dominican|url=http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/preps/kostas-antetokounmpo-making-a-name-for-himself-at-dominican-b99670083z1-368913091.html/|website=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=February 15, 2016}}</ref> where he played high school basketball during his junior and senior years. As a senior, he led his team to a state championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://daytonflyers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4218|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo \u2013 2016\u201317|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAfter high school, Antetokounmpo moved on to play [[college basketball]] at the [[University of Dayton]]. In the [[2016\u201317 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|2016\u201317 season]], his first with the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Flyers]], he was [[redshirt (college sports)|red-shirted]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.midmajormadness.com/2016/10/3/13148932/dayton-flyers-kostas-antetokounmpo-ineligible-redshirt-ncaa|title=Dayton's Kostas Antetokounmpo ruled ineligible for 2016\u201317|work=Mid-Major Madness|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> after being ruled a \"partial qualifier\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2016/10/03/kostas-antetokounmpo-ruled-ineligible-for-dayton/|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo ruled ineligible for Dayton|date=October 3, 2016|work=CollegeBasketballTalk|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> due to having spent his first two years of high school in Greece.<ref>[https://flyerfaithful.com/kostas-antetokounmpo-may-have-to-sit-the-2016-17-season-out-88140697b419 Kostas Antetokounmpo may have to sit the 2016\u201317 season out.]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He debuted in the [[2017\u201318 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|2017\u201318 season]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/kostas-antetokounmpo-1.html|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo College Stats {{!}} College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> averaging 5.2 points, 2.9 rebounds, 0.4 assists, 0.2 steals, and 1.1 blocks per game, in 15.1 minutes per game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/4066490/kostas-antetokounmpo|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo|publisher=ESPN|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Dallas Mavericks / Texas Legends (2018\u20132019)===\nOn March 22, 2018, Antetokounmpo declared for the [[2018 NBA draft]].<ref name=\"draft\">{{cite web|last1=Givony|first1=Jonathan|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo to test NBA draft waters|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/22873095/kostas-antetokounmpo-dayton-flyers-enter-nba-draft-test-waters|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> On May 4, 2018, Antetokounmpo would be one of a record-high 69 players to enter the [[NBA Draft Combine]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/complete-2018-nba-draft-combine-list-211843026.html|title=Some of college basketball's biggest names highlight NBA draft combine list|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Antetokounmpo was projected to be a second round selection, similar to his older brother [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]], due to his lack of notable progress in his redshirt freshman college season. He would ultimately wind up being the last pick of the [[2018 NBA draft]], after being selected by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], only to then be immediately traded to the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/dayton-draft-drought-ends-antetokounmpo-chosen-with-last-pick/LWtNcq9ztfmGFeZQZ9tS9L/|title=Dayton draft drought ends as Antetokounmpo chosen with last pick|newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]]|date=June 21, 2018|accessdate=June 22, 2018|first=David|last=Jablonski}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-acquire-draft-rights-to-ray-spalding-and-kostas-antetokounmpo/|title=Mavericks acquire draft rights to Ray Spalding and Kostas Antetokounmpo|date=June 21, 2018|access-date=June 21, 2018|publisher=mavs.com}}</ref> Antetokounmpo would later sign a [[two-way contract]] on July 13. Throughout the contract, he will split his playing time between the Mavericks and their [[NBA G League]] affiliate, the [[Texas Legends]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mavericks sign Kostas Antetokounmpo to two-way contract; waive Jalen Jones|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-sign-kostas-antetokounmpo-to-two-way-contract-waive-jalen-jones/|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref> He made his NBA debut on March 20, 2019 in a 118\u2013126 loss to the [[Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lillard scores 33 points, Blazers beat Mavericks 126\u2013118|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071746|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn July 19, 2019, Antetokounmpo was waived by the Mavericks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavsmoneyball.com/2019/7/19/20701354/dallas-mavericks-waive-kostas-antetokounmpo=21|title=Mavericks waive Kostas Antetokounmpo|date=July 19, 2019|website=mavsmoneyball.com|access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Lakers / South Bay Lakers (2019\u2013present)===\nAntetokounmpo was claimed off waivers by the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on July 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Report: Lakers claim Kostas Antetokounmpo off free agency waivers |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/07/21/report-lakers-claim-kostas-antetokounmpo-waivers |website=NBA |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lakers Awarded Kostas Antetokounmpo on Waiver Claim |url=https://www.nba.com/lakers/releases/190722-lakers-awarded-kostas-antetokounmpo-waiver-claim |website=Los Angeles Lakers |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nAntetokounmpo played with the junior [[Greece men's national under-20 basketball team|Greek Under-20 national team]]. He played at the [[2016 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship Division B]], where he won a bronze medal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/rpp//q/Ndubuisi%20ADETOKUNBO/pid/126901/_//players.html|title=archive.fiba.com: Players|website=archive.fiba.com|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> During the tournament, he averaged 1.3 points, 1.8 rebounds, and 0.3 assists per game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/126901/sid/12474/tid/291/_/2016_FIBA_U20_European_Championship_Division_B/index.html|title=Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo profile, FIBA U20 European Championship 2016 {{!}} FIBA.COM|work=FIBA.COM|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas]]\n| 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .000 || .000 || .500 || .5 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || 1.0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .000 || .000 || .500 || .5 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || 1.0\n{{S-end}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2017\u201318]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]]\n| 29 || 6 || 21.1 || .574 || .133 || .516 || 2.9 || .4 || .2 || 1.1 || 5.2\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAntetokounmpo was born in [[Athens]], Greece, to [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] parents. He officially became a full Greek citizen in 2016.<ref>[http://www.matrix24.gr/2016/01/vgazi-elliniko-diavatirio-o-kostas-antetokounmpo/ matrix24.gr \u0392\u03b3\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03b2\u03b1\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u03bf \u039a\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf {{in lang|el}}.]</ref> In addition, along with his younger sibling, Alexis, he has a Nigerian passport, which was granted to him in June 2013, so that he could gain a [[visa policy of the United States|visa]], and be allowed to legally enter into the United States.<ref>[http://www.gazzetta.gr/basketball/article/916698/i-halasmeni-kafetiera gazzetta.gr \u0397 \u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b7 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1  {{in lang|el}}.]</ref>\n\nHis late father, Charles, was a former Nigerian [[association football|soccer]] player, while his mother, Veronica, was a [[high jumper]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/09/26/226268651/nbas-g-bo-wants-to-bring-hope-to-greece-and-to-milwaukee|title=NBA Rookie Wants To Bring Hope To Greece, And To Milwaukee|publisher=NPR|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Charles died in September 2017, at age 54.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974785|title=Trail Blazers vs. Bucks \u2013 Game Recap \u2013 October 21, 2017|publisher=ESPN|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> His parents are from different Nigerian ethnic groups\u2014Charles was [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]], and Veronica is [[Igbo people|Igbo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/bucks-giannis-antetokounmpo-greek-freak-wants-to-go-back-to-his-nigerian-roots/ |title=\u2018The Greek Freak\u2019 wants to go back to his Nigerian roots |first=Marc J. |last=Spears |publisher=[[The Undefeated (website)|The Undefeated]] |date=March 5, 2019 |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> His oldest brother, Francis, is also a professional soccer player. He is a younger brother of [[Milwaukee Bucks]] players [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] and [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]]. He is also the older brother of Alex.<ref name=\"archdeacon\">{{cite web|last1=Archdeacon|first1=Tom|title=Flyers\u2019 Kostas Antetokounmpo tries to live up to his name|url=https://www.mydaytondailynews.com/sports/tom-archdeacon-flyers-kostas-antetokounmpo-tries-live-his-name/meHZJCKf9vQXNYVhHne5gL/|website=[[Dayton Daily News]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=September 23, 2017}}</ref> As a youth, Antetokounmpo played for the junior clubs of [[Filathlitikos B.C.|Filathlitikos]], which also developed his older brothers Thanasis and Giannis.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.proballers.com/basketball/player/66983/konstantinos-antetokounmpo Proballers.com Profile]\n*[http://www.nba.com/players/kostas/antetokounmpo/1628961 NBA.com profile]\n*[http://daytonflyers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4218&path= Dayton Flyers bio]\n\n{{Los Angeles Lakers current roster}}\n{{South Bay Lakers current roster}}\n{{2018 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antetokounmpo, Kostas}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks players]]\n[[Category:Dayton Flyers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Nigerian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Greek men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Igbo descent]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Igbo sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia 76ers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:South Bay Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Texas Legends players]]\n[[Category:Yoruba sportspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Greek basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Kostas Antetokounmpo\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| league = [[NBA]]\n| team = Los Angeles Lakers\n| number = 37\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lbs = 220\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|11|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Athens]], Greece\n| nationality = Greek\n| high_school = [[Dominican High School (Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin)|Dominican]]<br>([[Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin]])\n| college = [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]] (2017\u20132018)\n| draft_year = 2018\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 60\n| draft_team = [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n| career_start = 2018\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2018|full=y}}\n| team1 = [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n| years2 = 2018\u20132019\n| team2 = \u2192[[Texas Legends]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team3 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| years4 = 2019\u2013present\n| team4 = \u2192[[South Bay Lakers]]\n| profile = kostas_antetokounmpo\n| bbr = antetko01\n}}\n'''Kostas Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo''' ({{respell|AHN|teh|tuh|KOOM|poh|}}; {{lang-el|\u039a\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf}}) (born November 20, 1997)<ref>[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/126901/sid/12474/tid/291/_/2016_FIBA_U20_European_Championship_Division_B/index.html Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo DOB: 20 Nov.1997 Place of birth: Athens (GRE).]</ref> is a Greek professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), on a [[two-way contract]] with the [[South Bay Lakers]] of the [[NBA G League]]. He was drafted 60th overall by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] in the [[2018 NBA draft]], and his draft rights were then traded to the Dallas Mavericks.<ref name=\"realgm\">{{cite web|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo|url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Kostas-Antetokounmpo/Summary/93018|publisher=[[RealGM]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He attended and played [[college basketball|collegiate level basketball]] in the United States for the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton Flyers]]. Two of his older brothers, [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] and [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]], both play for the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lakers claim Giannis' younger brother, Kostas |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/27239420/lakers-claim-giannis-younger-brother-kostas |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 17, 2020 |date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAntetokounmpo was born in [[Sepolia]] in [[Athens, Greece]]. His parents were immigrants from [[Nigeria]]. As a youth, he began playing the sport of basketball with the junior youth teams of [[Filathlitikos BC|Filathlitikos]], in Athens.\n\n==High school career==\nAfter his older brother [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] was drafted by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] in the [[2013 NBA draft]], Antetokounmpo, along with his parents and his younger brother, Alexis, moved to Milwaukee. He attended [[Dominican High School (Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin)|Dominican High School]] in [[Whitefish Bay, Wisconsin]],<ref name=\"dominican\">{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Mark|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo making a name for himself at Dominican|url=http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/preps/kostas-antetokounmpo-making-a-name-for-himself-at-dominican-b99670083z1-368913091.html/|website=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=February 15, 2016}}</ref> where he played high school basketball during his junior and senior years. As a senior, he led his team to a state championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://daytonflyers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4218|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo \u2013 2016\u201317|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAfter high school, Antetokounmpo moved on to play [[college basketball]] at the [[University of Dayton]]. In the [[2016\u201317 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|2016\u201317 season]], his first with the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Flyers]], he was [[redshirt (college sports)|red-shirted]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.midmajormadness.com/2016/10/3/13148932/dayton-flyers-kostas-antetokounmpo-ineligible-redshirt-ncaa|title=Dayton's Kostas Antetokounmpo ruled ineligible for 2016\u201317|work=Mid-Major Madness|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> after being ruled a \"partial qualifier\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2016/10/03/kostas-antetokounmpo-ruled-ineligible-for-dayton/|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo ruled ineligible for Dayton|date=October 3, 2016|work=CollegeBasketballTalk|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> due to having spent his first two years of high school in Greece.<ref>[https://flyerfaithful.com/kostas-antetokounmpo-may-have-to-sit-the-2016-17-season-out-88140697b419 Kostas Antetokounmpo may have to sit the 2016\u201317 season out.]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He debuted in the [[2017\u201318 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|2017\u201318 season]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/kostas-antetokounmpo-1.html|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo College Stats {{!}} College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> averaging 5.2 points, 2.9 rebounds, 0.4 assists, 0.2 steals, and 1.1 blocks per game, in 15.1 minutes per game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/4066490/kostas-antetokounmpo|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo|publisher=ESPN|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Dallas Mavericks / Texas Legends (2018\u20132019)===\nOn March 22, 2018, Antetokounmpo declared for the [[2018 NBA draft]].<ref name=\"draft\">{{cite web|last1=Givony|first1=Jonathan|title=Kostas Antetokounmpo to test NBA draft waters|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/22873095/kostas-antetokounmpo-dayton-flyers-enter-nba-draft-test-waters|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> On May 4, 2018, Antetokounmpo would be one of a record-high 69 players to enter the [[NBA Draft Combine]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/complete-2018-nba-draft-combine-list-211843026.html|title=Some of college basketball's biggest names highlight NBA draft combine list|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Antetokounmpo was projected to be a second round selection, similar to his older brother [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]], due to his lack of notable progress in his redshirt freshman college season. He would ultimately wind up being the last pick of the [[2018 NBA draft]], after being selected by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], only to then be immediately traded to the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/dayton-draft-drought-ends-antetokounmpo-chosen-with-last-pick/LWtNcq9ztfmGFeZQZ9tS9L/|title=Dayton draft drought ends as Antetokounmpo chosen with last pick|newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]]|date=June 21, 2018|accessdate=June 22, 2018|first=David|last=Jablonski}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-acquire-draft-rights-to-ray-spalding-and-kostas-antetokounmpo/|title=Mavericks acquire draft rights to Ray Spalding and Kostas Antetokounmpo|date=June 21, 2018|access-date=June 21, 2018|publisher=mavs.com}}</ref> Antetokounmpo would later sign a [[two-way contract]] on July 13. Throughout the contract, he will split his playing time between the Mavericks and their [[NBA G League]] affiliate, the [[Texas Legends]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mavericks sign Kostas Antetokounmpo to two-way contract; waive Jalen Jones|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-sign-kostas-antetokounmpo-to-two-way-contract-waive-jalen-jones/|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref> He made his NBA debut on March 20, 2019 in a 118\u2013126 loss to the [[Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lillard scores 33 points, Blazers beat Mavericks 126\u2013118|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071746|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=March 20, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Lakers / South Bay Lakers (2019\u2013present)===\nOn July 19, 2019, Antetokounmpo was waived by the Mavericks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavsmoneyball.com/2019/7/19/20701354/dallas-mavericks-waive-kostas-antetokounmpo=21|title=Mavericks waive Kostas Antetokounmpo|date=July 19, 2019|website=mavsmoneyball.com|access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref> He would later be claimed by the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on July 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Report: Lakers claim Kostas Antetokounmpo off free agency waivers |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/07/21/report-lakers-claim-kostas-antetokounmpo-waivers |website=NBA |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lakers Awarded Kostas Antetokounmpo on Waiver Claim |url=https://www.nba.com/lakers/releases/190722-lakers-awarded-kostas-antetokounmpo-waiver-claim |website=Los Angeles Lakers |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nAntetokounmpo played with the junior [[Greece men's national under-20 basketball team|Greek Under-20 national team]]. He played at the [[2016 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship Division B]], where he won a bronze medal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/rpp//q/Ndubuisi%20ADETOKUNBO/pid/126901/_//players.html|title=archive.fiba.com: Players|website=archive.fiba.com|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> During the tournament, he averaged 1.3 points, 1.8 rebounds, and 0.3 assists per game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/126901/sid/12474/tid/291/_/2016_FIBA_U20_European_Championship_Division_B/index.html|title=Ndubuisi Antetokounmpo profile, FIBA U20 European Championship 2016 {{!}} FIBA.COM|work=FIBA.COM|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas]]\n| 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .000 || .000 || .500 || .5 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || 1.0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 2 || 0 || 5.5 || .000 || .000 || .500 || .5 || .0 || 1.0 || .0 || 1.0\n{{S-end}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2017\u201318]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]]\n| 29 || 6 || 21.1 || .574 || .133 || .516 || 2.9 || .4 || .2 || 1.1 || 5.2\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAntetokounmpo was born in [[Athens]], Greece, to [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] parents. He officially became a full Greek citizen in 2016.<ref>[http://www.matrix24.gr/2016/01/vgazi-elliniko-diavatirio-o-kostas-antetokounmpo/ matrix24.gr \u0392\u03b3\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03b2\u03b1\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u03bf \u039a\u03ce\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf {{in lang|el}}.]</ref> In addition, along with his younger sibling, Alexis, he has a Nigerian passport, which was granted to him in June 2013, so that he could gain a [[visa policy of the United States|visa]], and be allowed to legally enter into the United States.<ref>[http://www.gazzetta.gr/basketball/article/916698/i-halasmeni-kafetiera gazzetta.gr \u0397 \u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b7 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1  {{in lang|el}}.]</ref>\n\nHis late father, Charles, was a former Nigerian [[association football|soccer]] player, while his mother, Veronica, was a [[high jumper]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/09/26/226268651/nbas-g-bo-wants-to-bring-hope-to-greece-and-to-milwaukee|title=NBA Rookie Wants To Bring Hope To Greece, And To Milwaukee|publisher=NPR|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Charles died in September 2017, at age 54.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974785|title=Trail Blazers vs. Bucks \u2013 Game Recap \u2013 October 21, 2017|publisher=ESPN|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> His parents are from different Nigerian ethnic groups\u2014Charles was [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]], and Veronica is [[Igbo people|Igbo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/bucks-giannis-antetokounmpo-greek-freak-wants-to-go-back-to-his-nigerian-roots/ |title=\u2018The Greek Freak\u2019 wants to go back to his Nigerian roots |first=Marc J. |last=Spears |publisher=[[The Undefeated (website)|The Undefeated]] |date=March 5, 2019 |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> His oldest brother, Francis, is also a professional soccer player. He is a younger brother of [[Milwaukee Bucks]] players [[Giannis Antetokounmpo|Giannis]] and [[Thanasis Antetokounmpo|Thanasis]]. He is also the older brother of Alex.<ref name=\"archdeacon\">{{cite web|last1=Archdeacon|first1=Tom|title=Flyers\u2019 Kostas Antetokounmpo tries to live up to his name|url=https://www.mydaytondailynews.com/sports/tom-archdeacon-flyers-kostas-antetokounmpo-tries-live-his-name/meHZJCKf9vQXNYVhHne5gL/|website=[[Dayton Daily News]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=September 23, 2017}}</ref> As a youth, Antetokounmpo played for the junior clubs of [[Filathlitikos B.C.|Filathlitikos]], which also developed his older brothers Thanasis and Giannis.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.proballers.com/basketball/player/66983/konstantinos-antetokounmpo Proballers.com Profile]\n*[http://www.nba.com/players/kostas/antetokounmpo/1628961 NBA.com profile]\n*[http://daytonflyers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4218&path= Dayton Flyers bio]\n\n{{Los Angeles Lakers current roster}}\n{{South Bay Lakers current roster}}\n{{2018 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antetokounmpo, Kostas}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks players]]\n[[Category:Dayton Flyers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Nigerian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Greek men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Igbo descent]]\n[[Category:Greek people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Igbo sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia 76ers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:South Bay Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Texas Legends p