{"title_page": "Millie Scott", "text_new": "'''Millie Scott''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] [[singing|singer]], who had moderate success in the [[United States|US]] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B]] [[record chart|chart]] during the 1980s.\n\n==Biography==\nScott was born in [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] on the coast of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. She first sang [[gospel music|gospel]], before becoming a [[jazz]] singer. After moving to [[New York City|New York]], she was enticed to move to [[Detroit]] by [[The Temptations]], and she remains in Detroit to this day.<ref>[http://www.soulwalking.co.uk/Millie%20Scott.html Millie Scott], SoulWalking, accessed December 2010</ref>\n\nIn 1971 she formed the group [[Quiet Elegance]] along with [[Lois Reeves]] and Frankie Gearing. They toured with [[The Temptations]] and signed to the [[Hi Records]] label in 1972, releasing a number of singles. In 1986, she was signed to D&B Productions in Detroit, helmed by [[Bruce Nazarian]], whose [[sound recording and reproduction|recordings]] led to Scott being signed as a solo artist to [[Island Records]] and releasing her debut [[Single (music)|single]], \"Prisoner Of Love\". It peaked at #52 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in 1986. One of the tracks from her later albums is \"Lets Talk It Over\" which is a mellow dance track appreciated by those who preferred less of the electronic sound associated with that period.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 485}}</ref>\n\nHer other songs include \"Prisoner of Love\", \"Automatic\" and \"Ev'ry Little Bit\". Scott made numerous appearances on the [[United Kingdom|UK]] [[Channel 4]] [[television program]]me ''Solid Soul'' in the mid-1980s, alongside other R&B acts such as [[Loose Ends (band)|Loose Ends]] and [[Ruby Turner]].\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio Albums===\n* ''Love Me Right'' (1987)\n* ''I Can Make It Good For You'' (1988)\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Automatic\" (1986) - UK#56 / US R&B#49\n* \"Prisoner Of Love\" (1986) - UK#52 / US Dance#13 / Us R&B#78\n* \"Love Me Right\" (1987) - Us R&B#40\n* \"Ev'ry Little Bit\" (1987) - UK#63 / US R&B#11\n* \"To The Letter\" (1988) \n* \"A Love Of Your Own\" (1988) - US R&B#66\n* \"It's My Life\" (1988) - US R&B#90\n<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/artist/64135-Millie-Scott Album and Singles Discography]. ''Discogs.com''. Retrieved 21 October 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/23212/millie-scott/ UK Chart Information]. ''Officialcharts.com''. Retrieved 21 October 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Millie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Millie Scott''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] [[singing|singer]], who had moderate success in the [[United States|US]] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B]] [[record chart|chart]] during the 1980s.\n\n==Biography==\nScott was born in [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] on the coast of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. She first sang [[gospel music|gospel]], before becoming a [[jazz]] singer. After moving to [[New York City|New York]], she was enticed to move to [[Detroit]] by [[The Temptations]], and she remains in Detroit to this day.<ref>[http://www.soulwalking.co.uk/Millie%20Scott.html Millie Scott], SoulWalking, accessed December 2010</ref> \n\nIn 1971 she formed the group [[Quiet Elegance]] along with [[Lois Reeves]] and Frankie Gearing. They toured with [[The Temptations]] and signed to the [[Hi Records]] label in 1972, releasing a number of singles. In 1986, she was signed to D&B Productions in Detroit, helmed by [[Bruce Nazarian]], whose [[sound recording and reproduction|recordings]] led to Scott being signed as a solo artist to [[Island Records]] and releasing her debut [[Single (music)|single]], \"Prisoner Of Love\". It peaked at #52 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in 1986. One of the tracks from her later albums is \"Lets Talk It Over\" which is a mellow dance track appreciated by those who preferred less of the electronic sound associated with that period.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 485}}</ref>\n\nHer other songs include \"Prisoner of Love\", \"Automatic\" and \"Ev'ry Little Bit\". Scott made numerous appearances on the [[United Kingdom|UK]] [[Channel 4]] [[television program]]me ''Solid Soul'' in the mid-1980s, alongside other R&B acts such as [[Loose Ends (band)|Loose Ends]] and [[Ruby Turner]].\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio Albums===\n* ''Love Me Right'' (1987)\n* ''I Can Make It Good For You'' (1988)\n===Singles===\n* \"Automatic\" (1986) - UK#56 / US R&B#49\n* \"Prisoner Of Love\" (1986) - UK#52 / US Dance#13 / Us R&B#78\n* \"Love Me Right\" (1987) - Us R&B#40\n* \"Ev'ry Little Bit\" (1987) - UK#63 / US R&B#11\n* \"To The Letter\" (1988) \n* \"A Love Of Your Own\" (1988) - US R&B#66\n* \"It's My Life\" (1988) - US R&B#90\n<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/artist/64135-Millie-Scott Album and Singles Discography]. ''Discogs.com''. Retrieved 21 October 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/23212/millie-scott/ UK Chart Infomation]. ''Officialcharts.com''. Retrieved 21 October 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Millie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Musicians fr